This paper is primarily focused on a graph transformation technique called bubbling, which is used for executing non-deterministic steps in functional logic computations. Therefore, the most likely category is cs.PL (Programming Languages), which deals with the design, implementation, and analysis of programming languages and their associated tools and methodologies. 

The paper also discusses the correctness and efficiency of the bubbling technique, which involves graph manipulation and maintenance of certain attributes of the nodes. This suggests that it could also be relevant to categories such as cs.LO (Logic in Computer Science), cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms), and cs.SE (Software Engineering). 

Finally, the paper proposes a novel algorithm for executing bubbling steps that only requires local information, which could be of interest to researchers in the field of cs.FL (Formal Languages and Automata Theory), which deals with the study of formal languages, grammars, and automata.
